and kind of talk about the process that Bruce and I went

20
00:00:36,133 --> 00:00:40,615
through to create this game called Civilization.

21
00:00:42,175 --> 00:00:47,197
And we will get to our next slide here somehow or not.

22
00:00:52,239 --> 00:00:52,619
There we go.

23
00:00:54,348 --> 00:00:59,811
So, the approach we want to take is kind of talk about the thought process that we went through

24
00:00:59,831 --> 00:01:09,255
to create the game. With the hindsight of 25 years, a lot of things that we did seemed to be the

25
00:01:09,295 --> 00:01:13,577
right thing to do. Some of the things we did turned out to be the wrong thing to do. But we

26
00:01:13,617 --> 00:01:18,099
would like to justify even the wrong things, explain why we did them that way, and what we

27
00:01:18,139 --> 00:01:21,841
were thinking at the time. It was kind of a...

28
00:01:23,683 --> 00:01:26,144
audacious game for us to make.

29
00:01:26,224 --> 00:01:29,505
And the idea that we were gonna kind of compress

30
00:01:30,005 --> 00:01:33,686
the entire history of civilization into a computer game,

31
00:01:34,886 --> 00:01:38,548
not only the actual history, but every possible history

32
00:01:38,568 --> 00:01:40,208
that could have happened of civilization,

33
00:01:41,468 --> 00:01:43,149
we were trying to put into this game.

34
00:01:44,109 --> 00:01:48,711
It was a time when we were young and audacious.

35
00:01:49,531 --> 00:01:52,073
And we had just finished Railroad Tycoon,

36
00:01:52,093 --> 00:01:55,136
which is kind of the first God game that we worked on.

37
00:01:56,417 --> 00:01:58,038
We were working on Covert Action,

38
00:01:58,098 --> 00:02:00,680
which was an attempt to write

39
00:02:00,880 --> 00:02:02,782
a computer-generated mystery novel.

40
00:02:03,202 --> 00:02:04,203
Didn't quite turn out that way,

41
00:02:04,263 --> 00:02:06,365
but that was kind of our goal at the beginning.

42
00:02:06,425 --> 00:02:07,586
We had just finished Pirates,

43
00:02:07,626 --> 00:02:09,727
which was one of the very first open-world kind of games.

44
00:02:09,767 --> 00:02:12,810
So it was a time when we were

45
00:02:13,651 --> 00:02:16,373
We thought we could do anything and sure,

46
00:02:16,413 --> 00:02:18,014
let's take on the history of civilization

47
00:02:18,074 --> 00:02:19,195
and make a game out of that.

48
00:02:19,856 --> 00:02:22,898
Both Bruce and I are kind of interested in history

49
00:02:23,518 --> 00:02:26,941
and have a background in war gaming and other things

50
00:02:26,961 --> 00:02:28,583
which kind of ended up showing up

51
00:02:28,683 --> 00:02:29,984
in the game of civilization.

52
00:02:30,064 --> 00:02:34,247
But the way that I remember the,

53
00:02:34,928 --> 00:02:37,350
for those of you that are not familiar with civilization,

54
00:02:37,390 --> 00:02:39,331
it's the game about world history, okay.

55
00:02:41,843 --> 00:02:47,156
It starts in the Stone Age and you end up by going to Alpha Centauri, taking humanity

56
00:02:47,216 --> 00:02:48,038
into space.

57
00:02:49,281 --> 00:02:50,985
6,000 years of human history.

58
00:02:52,079 --> 00:02:52,940
in 640K.

59
00:02:54,321 --> 00:02:57,684
So the, as I remember the story, Bruce and I were,

60
00:02:57,704 --> 00:03:01,327
I remember us riding on a train up to New York, I think,

61
00:03:01,407 --> 00:03:04,790
and we had recently completed Railroad Tycoon,

62
00:03:05,751 --> 00:03:07,572
and really enjoyed that experience,

63
00:03:07,592 --> 00:03:10,875
that kind of God game-ish, start with something small,

64
00:03:11,035 --> 00:03:11,416
build it.

65
00:03:12,276 --> 00:03:16,758
Use your own creativity to basically tell a different story every time you play.

66
00:03:17,618 --> 00:03:21,920
The idea of different systems kind of working together, the operation of the railroads,

67
00:03:21,940 --> 00:03:24,501
the building of the railroads, the financing of the railroads,

68
00:03:25,481 --> 00:03:28,502
maintaining your locomotives, routing your trains,

69
00:03:29,523 --> 00:03:35,365
lots of fun little pieces that kind of came together to make a lot of interesting decisions.

70
00:03:36,345 --> 00:03:40,067
And we were looking for another topic that would have those

71
00:03:40,127 --> 00:03:41,248
kind of qualities to it.

72
00:03:42,028 --> 00:03:46,690
And somehow we thought, well, history has a lot of that

73
00:03:46,990 --> 00:03:47,530
going on.

74
00:03:48,311 --> 00:03:52,332
And it's kind of the ultimate God game, starting with one

75
00:03:52,893 --> 00:03:57,375
little village back in 4000 BC and seeing how far we could go

76
00:03:57,415 --> 00:03:57,635
with it.

77
00:03:59,538 --> 00:04:02,327
That's how I remember it. I'm not sure Bruce how you remember it.

78
00:04:02,347 --> 00:04:05,478
I just remember we talked a lot about that kind of stuff.

79
00:04:07,143 --> 00:04:12,747
Sid always had like a half a dozen prototypes on his computer. He was always noodling a new game idea, you know

80
00:04:12,787 --> 00:04:17,690
And now we look at it. He'd we talk about it. Maybe he's something he wouldn't tell me about it. Then I remember

81
00:04:17,770 --> 00:04:20,291
These conversations went on we played a lot of

82
00:04:21,012 --> 00:04:24,974
Empire deluxe and we talked about you gave me a task to come up with ten things

83
00:04:25,094 --> 00:04:30,577
I would change about Empire deluxe if I could change anything and trying to be a progressive person

84
00:04:30,637 --> 00:04:33,439
I came up with 12 and gave him the list and

85
00:04:33,619 --> 00:04:35,801
and and then one day

86
00:04:37,351 --> 00:04:40,293
a disc pops into my desk, and I have it at home.

87
00:04:40,513 --> 00:04:43,455
It's a five and a quarter inch floppy disc from May of 1990,

88
00:04:43,936 --> 00:04:46,317
and it's the first playable version of Civilization

89
00:04:46,357 --> 00:04:48,278
anybody had ever seen other than his computer.

90
00:04:48,879 --> 00:04:50,580
I saved this as a historic artifact.

91
00:04:50,620 --> 00:04:52,281
I hadn't saved the first version of Railroad Deck,

92
00:04:52,341 --> 00:04:54,563
and I determined to save whatever was coming down

93
00:04:54,583 --> 00:04:56,064
the pipe next, I'd save the first version.

94
00:04:56,084 --> 00:04:57,325
So that's my memory.

95
00:04:57,345 --> 00:04:58,906
We had played all these other games,

96
00:04:58,966 --> 00:05:01,848
and then this came together enough for you to feel

97
00:05:01,868 --> 00:05:03,569
that it was good enough for somebody else to look at.

98
00:05:04,692 --> 00:05:10,754
Yeah, I think we need to give credit to Empire as part of the inspiration for Civ, also SimCity,

99
00:05:11,214 --> 00:05:12,294
also Railroad Tycoon.

100
00:05:12,434 --> 00:05:16,676
There's also a board game actually called Civilization that was out there at the time.

101
00:05:16,716 --> 00:05:17,256
We played that.

102
00:05:17,276 --> 00:05:17,756
We played that.

103
00:05:17,836 --> 00:05:21,538
Francis Trusham designed it in England and Avalon Hill had published an American version

104
00:05:21,558 --> 00:05:21,718
of it.

105
00:05:22,837 --> 00:05:24,617
We stirred all those ingredients together.

106
00:05:25,538 --> 00:05:27,739
We're going to claim that the topic was one of the things we

107
00:05:27,779 --> 00:05:30,980
did right in Civilization, that it was a good topic.

108
00:05:31,220 --> 00:05:34,502
It really lent itself to the kind of games we wanted to

109
00:05:34,522 --> 00:05:37,163
make and the place we were with the technology.

110
00:05:37,864 --> 00:05:38,965
in those games.

111
00:05:39,005 --> 00:05:41,067
And also it had a huge potential audience.

112
00:05:41,087 --> 00:05:43,609
I mean, one of my talking points over the years has been

113
00:05:44,009 --> 00:05:46,432
when you start a project, your potential customer

114
00:05:46,932 --> 00:05:49,635
is everybody who has the platform that game is gonna be on.

115
00:05:49,675 --> 00:05:51,577
But as soon as you make decisions about what that game is about,

116
00:05:51,877 --> 00:05:53,539
you start to shrink your potential audience.

117
00:05:53,599 --> 00:05:56,161
Well, the history of civilization is a pretty big topic,

118
00:05:56,221 --> 00:05:58,223
so we had a huge potential audience.

119
00:05:58,263 --> 00:06:00,605
Remember, later on when Sid gave the first presentation

120
00:06:00,625 --> 00:06:01,846
I ever heard about game design.

121
00:06:02,719 --> 00:06:04,801
He, one of his topic points was choose a big topic.

122
00:06:04,841 --> 00:06:06,262
I said, I think we'd already made Civilization

123
00:06:06,282 --> 00:06:07,123
by that time, I'm not sure, but I said,

124
00:06:07,143 --> 00:06:08,004
well, there can't be a bigger one

125
00:06:08,024 --> 00:06:09,406
than the history of Civilization.

126
00:06:10,267 --> 00:06:13,150
Yeah, we talk about trying to make games epic.

127
00:06:13,190 --> 00:06:14,711
The fact that it really doesn't cost any more

128
00:06:15,172 --> 00:06:17,835
to make a game epic than to make it non-epic.

129
00:06:20,063 --> 00:06:23,604
So the next thing that we kind of had to figure out

130
00:06:23,644 --> 00:06:25,624
was how are we gonna approach this topic?

131
00:06:25,744 --> 00:06:27,785
Obviously there could be many, many different games

132
00:06:27,845 --> 00:06:29,605
written on the topic of civilization.

133
00:06:29,645 --> 00:06:32,206
So how are we gonna approach this?

134
00:06:33,166 --> 00:06:36,207
One of the ideas that really, I think, paid off for us

135
00:06:36,807 --> 00:06:39,368
was the idea of starting very small

136
00:06:39,448 --> 00:06:41,428
with that first settler, that first city.

137
00:06:43,049 --> 00:06:44,389
The topic could be intimidating.

138
00:06:44,989 --> 00:06:51,652
So I think allowing you to start with a very simple problem,

139
00:06:52,052 --> 00:06:55,053
very simple situation, founding that first city,

140
00:06:55,153 --> 00:06:58,335
that led to something else, the first settler,

141
00:06:58,415 --> 00:07:00,295
the first unit, exploring.

142
00:07:01,496 --> 00:07:03,017
So that was one of the ideas that we had

143
00:07:03,717 --> 00:07:05,538
in terms of the tone and the approach.

144
00:07:06,938 --> 00:07:10,960
Another one was to, there's a strange mixture to me

145
00:07:10,980 --> 00:07:12,961
in looking back at Civ I of humor,

146
00:07:13,801 --> 00:07:15,401
and incredible seriousness.

147
00:07:15,441 --> 00:07:17,962
Like some parts of it, you know,

148
00:07:18,042 --> 00:07:21,363
here's the lions defeat gladiators, seven to nothing.

149
00:07:23,143 --> 00:07:25,264
You know, that was our attempt at humor.

150
00:07:26,264 --> 00:07:29,065
Our little friend Elvis here in our city screen.

151
00:07:29,125 --> 00:07:30,605
So there are ways that we wanted to make

152
00:07:30,845 --> 00:07:33,386
the history of civilization kind of non-intimidating

153
00:07:34,026 --> 00:07:34,886
and friendly.

154
00:07:36,567 --> 00:07:39,148
But then again, there's the Civilopedia,

155
00:07:39,188 --> 00:07:40,589
where we have an entry here, you know,

156
00:07:40,989 --> 00:07:45,592
trying to make this game feel deep and important

157
00:07:45,932 --> 00:07:48,594
and something that you should have your kids

158
00:07:48,654 --> 00:07:49,694
and your parents play.

159
00:07:50,295 --> 00:07:55,098
And so we were really trying to figure this out

160
00:07:55,138 --> 00:07:56,779
as we went along, and there were no...

161
00:07:57,579 --> 00:08:04,484
civilization games before us to guide us as to what we should do. So we kind of dipped our toe in a lot of different areas.

162
00:08:06,126 --> 00:08:13,771
But the bottom line to me, I think, and Bruce, maybe you have a thought about this, is that the game was fun to play when we started.

163
00:08:14,092 --> 00:08:20,857
And as long as that was true, I think we felt we were on the right track, whether our jokes were lame or not.

164
00:08:21,878 --> 00:08:24,720
The game was fun, and I think that kind of what kept us going at the end.

165
00:08:24,820 --> 00:08:26,261
I think we learned the idea that,

166
00:08:26,281 --> 00:08:27,722
I come up with this term called

167
00:08:27,742 --> 00:08:29,403
the inverted pyramid of decision making,

168
00:08:29,443 --> 00:08:31,605
where the game starts with one little

169
00:08:31,645 --> 00:08:32,606
settler unit on the board,

170
00:08:32,626 --> 00:08:33,586
and you have a decision,

171
00:08:33,626 --> 00:08:35,768
what direction that person, that unit moves.

172
00:08:36,208 --> 00:08:38,210
And quickly you've got cities and more units,

173
00:08:38,290 --> 00:08:40,251
and the number of decisions you have,

174
00:08:40,652 --> 00:08:42,013
your choices go up like this.

175
00:08:42,493 --> 00:08:44,194
I called it the inverted pyramid of decision making.

176
00:08:44,554 --> 00:08:46,095
Now years later, I came up with the idea

177
00:08:46,115 --> 00:08:48,157
that you had 15 minutes at that time

178
00:08:48,577 --> 00:08:49,958
to engage someone in your game,

179
00:08:50,078 --> 00:08:51,779
otherwise you might lose them and they'd be gone.

180
00:08:52,260 --> 00:08:54,001
I think today we'd face a situation

181
00:08:54,041 --> 00:08:55,182
where you have two or three minutes

182
00:08:55,202 --> 00:08:56,983
to get somebody interested in a game today,

183
00:08:57,343 --> 00:08:59,605
but then we had more time, and I thought we did.

184
00:08:59,625 --> 00:09:01,206
I think we borrowed from other guys,

185
00:09:01,226 --> 00:09:03,528
or like Empire Deluxe,

186
00:09:03,548 --> 00:09:05,349
you started with just something simpler and it grew.

187
00:09:05,829 --> 00:09:07,751
We captured that same sense, I think,

188
00:09:07,771 --> 00:09:09,452
and I think that was a good, we did that well.

189
00:09:09,632 --> 00:09:10,553
Or you did that well, let's say.

190
00:09:11,033 --> 00:09:14,675
Yeah, I think our gift was to know what to steal from other games.

191
00:09:15,496 --> 00:09:18,198
Yeah, how much to borrow and how much to invent yourself.

192
00:09:19,579 --> 00:09:19,719
So

193
00:09:23,517 --> 00:09:25,339
Was this a good, did we do this right or wrong?

194
00:09:25,359 --> 00:09:26,981
I think the jury is still out.

195
00:09:27,301 --> 00:09:31,146
When you look at how the Civilization series has evolved,

196
00:09:32,307 --> 00:09:34,910
humor has not necessarily been a big part

197
00:09:34,950 --> 00:09:36,211
of the succeeding Civ games,

198
00:09:36,792 --> 00:09:38,854
but it was really an indication

199
00:09:38,934 --> 00:09:41,236
of kind of how unsure we were about.

200
00:09:43,378 --> 00:09:47,040
Was this game going to be taken seriously by players,

201
00:09:47,200 --> 00:09:50,262
or was it something we needed to really kind of lighten up

202
00:09:50,322 --> 00:09:51,783
and make more accessible in that way?

203
00:09:51,803 --> 00:09:53,664
I think we found a good balance. I mean, I felt good about it.

204
00:09:53,684 --> 00:09:57,006
One little point I made a note of is that I think we did a good job

205
00:09:57,086 --> 00:10:00,548
of telling the players that he or she was doing a good job.

206
00:10:00,948 --> 00:10:04,050
We loved the King Day parades, and there was other notices,

207
00:10:04,090 --> 00:10:05,311
the newspaper reports, and...

208
00:10:06,072 --> 00:10:07,577
That was all the ways that we were telling the player,

209
00:10:07,597 --> 00:10:09,843
you're doing great, keep going, you're super,

210
00:10:09,943 --> 00:10:11,648
you're doing a great job as king of this country.

211
00:10:12,089 --> 00:10:14,135
I think we did that well.

212
00:10:14,919 --> 00:10:16,800
I think that's always a question in games as you're playing,

213
00:10:16,820 --> 00:10:18,001
am I doing the right thing?

214
00:10:18,061 --> 00:10:18,901
Am I on the right track?

215
00:10:19,402 --> 00:10:22,104
Have I spent the last hour or two wasting my time?

216
00:10:22,704 --> 00:10:25,206
Giving the player those constant indications

217
00:10:25,246 --> 00:10:29,029
that this is progress, this is the right thing to do,

218
00:10:29,149 --> 00:10:32,371
or we're watching, we're appreciating what you're doing,

219
00:10:32,451 --> 00:10:36,174
is encouraging to the player to allow them to keep going.

220
00:10:38,343 --> 00:10:41,445
One thing that I guess in hindsight seems so obvious,

221
00:10:41,545 --> 00:10:45,368
but we really could not call this game Civilization

222
00:10:45,508 --> 00:10:46,829
as it was in development.

223
00:10:47,290 --> 00:10:48,551
That was kind of our code name,

224
00:10:48,591 --> 00:10:49,651
that was our internal name,

225
00:10:49,671 --> 00:10:52,073
but our assumption was that this game

226
00:10:52,093 --> 00:10:53,294
would not be called Civilization

227
00:10:53,334 --> 00:10:54,815
because there was a board game out there

228
00:10:55,376 --> 00:10:57,417
called Civilization, it was owned by Avalon Hill,

229
00:10:57,457 --> 00:10:58,938
which was another computer game

230
00:10:59,239 --> 00:11:00,539
publishing company at the time.

231
00:11:01,222 --> 00:11:05,245
And the game had originally been designed in England.

232
00:11:05,946 --> 00:11:09,869
So we were trying to come up with alternative names.

233
00:11:09,989 --> 00:11:12,691
And I don't remember.

234
00:11:12,711 --> 00:11:17,294
Call to Power, Rise of Nations, Age of Empires,

235
00:11:17,334 --> 00:11:18,555
you know, names like that.

236
00:11:18,635 --> 00:11:25,381
But we said, you know, the only appropriate name

237
00:11:25,421 --> 00:11:26,922
for this game is Civilization.

238
00:11:27,022 --> 00:11:29,824
So our intrepid.

239
00:11:30,549 --> 00:11:37,232
marketing team went to talk to Avalon Hill, and amazingly enough, they were able to work

240
00:11:37,292 --> 00:11:41,715
out an arrangement there. I think Avalon Hill was maybe withdrawing somewhat from the computer

241
00:11:41,975 --> 00:11:48,438
side of things at the time, and we were able to get the name to Civilization, which I think

242
00:11:48,958 --> 00:11:55,421
is actually a pretty significant part of the success of the game. When you look back at

243
00:11:55,461 --> 00:11:56,282
the games that we've done...

244
00:11:57,262 --> 00:12:00,943
Pirates, exclamation point, railroad tycoon.

245
00:12:01,183 --> 00:12:05,164
I mean, it's those names that kind of create a picture

246
00:12:05,184 --> 00:12:07,365
in your mind almost immediately of what the game might be

247
00:12:07,845 --> 00:12:09,585
that helped them to be successful.

248
00:12:10,506 --> 00:12:12,686
And I also actually credit this image

249
00:12:12,846 --> 00:12:15,227
that one of our marketing people was able to find.

250
00:12:16,327 --> 00:12:17,848
This was not created for the game.

251
00:12:17,868 --> 00:12:19,789
It was actually found.

252
00:12:19,950 --> 00:12:24,873
But it captures, again, the potential, the possibilities

253
00:12:24,933 --> 00:12:28,014
of what your game experience is going to be.

254
00:12:30,096 --> 00:12:33,157
The other point that I'll make is that our game did not really

255
00:12:34,410 --> 00:12:36,131
duplicate the board game?

256
00:12:36,431 --> 00:12:38,332
I get that question fairly often.

257
00:12:38,832 --> 00:12:43,133
The board game was limited to a specific geographic area and a

258
00:12:43,193 --> 00:12:46,014
specific era of time.

259
00:12:46,955 --> 00:12:49,495
There were some cool ideas in there, but I think we added a

260
00:12:50,396 --> 00:12:52,296
few of our own as we went along.

261
00:12:53,997 --> 00:12:56,938
But this, I think, was a huge win for us to be able to use

262
00:12:56,998 --> 00:13:00,279
the name Civilization for the game that we were making.

263
00:13:05,513 --> 00:13:07,875
Okay, here we go.

264
00:13:10,517 --> 00:13:13,899
This is the, kind of the classic.

265
00:13:14,918 --> 00:13:21,381
perception of Civ is that it is the turn-based game. The

266
00:13:21,441 --> 00:13:26,564
turn-based-ishness is at the heart of Civilization. And

267
00:13:27,524 --> 00:13:32,347
interestingly enough, the first version of the game, probably

268
00:13:32,367 --> 00:13:37,509
the one that Bruce has the disc of, was not turn-based. It was

269
00:13:38,170 --> 00:13:39,110
more of a SimCity

270
00:13:40,797 --> 00:13:43,820
zone this area for farms, zone this area for,

271
00:13:44,421 --> 00:13:47,144
kind of watch things evolve over time.

272
00:13:48,225 --> 00:13:51,749
And it was really when we switched over

273
00:13:51,809 --> 00:13:55,152
to a turn-based mode that the game came together.

274
00:13:57,096 --> 00:14:02,619
At that point, the player became totally engaged in what was happening, but was given enough

275
00:14:02,699 --> 00:14:06,161
time to really consider the implications of what they were doing.

276
00:14:07,422 --> 00:14:10,163
They had, could project into the future.

277
00:14:10,804 --> 00:14:15,326
What I like to think about Civilization is it's a game where you are always, your mind

278
00:14:15,386 --> 00:14:16,387
is always ahead of the game.

279
00:14:16,487 --> 00:14:17,627
You're always anticipating.

280
00:14:18,668 --> 00:14:24,977
What's going to happen next you have a couple of things a wonder being built over here. You're exploring this continent over here

281
00:14:24,997 --> 00:14:29,123
You've always got a couple things going on that you're looking towards and that

282
00:14:29,323 --> 00:14:34,110
You know that kind of feeds into that one more turn or that one more technology or one more

283
00:14:36,896 --> 00:14:39,157
You're always kind of leaning forward into the future.

284
00:14:40,297 --> 00:14:43,359
Very interesting, of course Bruce went on to Ensemble

285
00:14:43,439 --> 00:14:47,621
to create Age of Empires there, which was turn-based,

286
00:14:47,761 --> 00:14:49,242
I mean it was real-time.

287
00:14:50,663 --> 00:14:55,405
In my mind, the reason those games are so different

288
00:14:55,585 --> 00:14:59,627
is almost solely based on the fact that one is turn-based

289
00:14:59,747 --> 00:15:01,208
and one is real-time.

290
00:15:03,370 --> 00:15:06,811
Bruce, do you have anything to say about that?

291
00:15:06,851 --> 00:15:10,713
Well, Age of Empires was like five or six years later,

292
00:15:10,813 --> 00:15:12,853
and the world had changed a little bit.

293
00:15:12,873 --> 00:15:14,534
The strategy games, you know, there had been Command

294
00:15:14,574 --> 00:15:16,855
and Conquer had been published, and Warcraft had been

295
00:15:16,875 --> 00:15:18,415
published, and these were real-time strategy games,

296
00:15:18,435 --> 00:15:18,715
and they were.

297
00:15:19,585 --> 00:15:25,148
Extremely successful and so my my colleagues and I were we wanted we needed to do something different

298
00:15:25,188 --> 00:15:30,671
We but we love civilization, but we want to do something different. We said can we do civilization in real time?

299
00:15:30,772 --> 00:15:33,813
What would that be like? Would that be it'd be different enough?

300
00:15:33,833 --> 00:15:36,535
It wouldn't be you know be borrowing but we wouldn't be borrowing everything

301
00:15:37,095 --> 00:15:41,478
It would be different enough to be a new a new product and it turned out it was I mean it was more than just

302
00:15:42,218 --> 00:15:43,259
real time but at real time

303
00:15:43,830 --> 00:15:45,911
Also, our games were played in like an hour.

304
00:15:45,931 --> 00:15:48,032
Age of Empires was an hour, half hour experience,

305
00:15:48,072 --> 00:15:49,193
where Civilization was a different,

306
00:15:49,613 --> 00:15:50,854
longer experience usually.

307
00:15:51,654 --> 00:15:54,336
So we're trying to adjust to the marketplace

308
00:15:54,476 --> 00:15:57,297
and take advantage of things that had changed.

309
00:15:57,317 --> 00:16:00,799
I think it's nice that both games existed

310
00:16:00,879 --> 00:16:02,460
and did really well.

311
00:16:03,841 --> 00:16:05,222
And we also did other things too.

312
00:16:05,482 --> 00:16:07,263
We telescoped our time period.

313
00:16:07,643 --> 00:16:09,965
Age one was just Ancients and then age two was.

314
00:16:10,533 --> 00:16:14,395
was the knights and castles, which was the sweet spot,

315
00:16:14,435 --> 00:16:15,095
really turned out.

316
00:16:15,155 --> 00:16:18,016
But yeah, it was certainly influenced.

317
00:16:18,036 --> 00:16:20,578
The vision for Age was let's take civilization,

318
00:16:20,638 --> 00:16:22,959
move it into real-time strategy and historical framework,

319
00:16:23,019 --> 00:16:24,379
and that was the vision.

320
00:16:24,987 --> 00:16:31,675
Yeah, it just strikes me that a lot of the differences are based on that, that you can't play a

321
00:16:31,715 --> 00:16:38,582
real-time game for 20 hours. It would be too intense. And by the same token, a turn-based

322
00:16:38,623 --> 00:16:44,069
game that lasted 30 minutes or so, again, would not really be satisfying.

323
00:16:45,170 --> 00:16:49,652
It's, I think this issue of turn-based versus real-time

324
00:16:50,072 --> 00:16:53,414
has so many implications in terms of where the games go,

325
00:16:53,474 --> 00:16:56,075
again, given the similar subject matter.

326
00:16:56,095 --> 00:17:00,917
So, it was not, we did not realize at the time

327
00:17:00,957 --> 00:17:05,300
that we had made this pretty significant switch

328
00:17:05,800 --> 00:17:07,761
and the whole one more turn phenomenon.

329
00:17:08,461 --> 00:17:12,484
had not really occurred to us. It's something that just arose

330
00:17:12,644 --> 00:17:15,886
out of the development of the game. Looking back it seems to

331
00:17:15,926 --> 00:17:22,150
be so characteristic of Civ, but it was a way of just getting you

332
00:17:22,230 --> 00:17:24,612
closer to the action and getting you more involved in what was

333
00:17:24,632 --> 00:17:27,974
happening. At the same time giving you enough time to

334
00:17:28,054 --> 00:17:29,095
consider your decisions.

335
00:17:30,056 --> 00:17:37,862
Really allowing us to do things like the tech tree and diplomacy, all the different things that you take some time to do in the game.

336
00:17:38,583 --> 00:17:43,567
We're really based on this fact that we switched over to a turn-based mode.

337
00:17:45,488 --> 00:17:50,232
Probably it was fairly uncommon in games of that time, I'd have to say.

338
00:17:50,252 --> 00:18:00,139
A lot of our background was in wargaming, which is clearly turn-based or movement-based or player-time-scale based.

339
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:08,625
And that probably influenced a lot of what we did there, but at the time it was fairly different from what was going on there.

340
00:18:09,906 --> 00:18:10,947
As well as the fact that...

341
00:18:12,117 --> 00:18:15,622
The whole idea of doing a strategy game was kind of unique at that time.

342
00:18:15,682 --> 00:18:19,366
And there were a few games out there, but strategy games were generally considered

343
00:18:20,788 --> 00:18:28,237
slow-moving, boring, nerd-oriented, and setting up a bunch of counters on a map.

344
00:18:29,643 --> 00:18:33,564
And it was not something that computers were supposed to be

345
00:18:34,545 --> 00:18:35,805
fun for computer game players.

346
00:18:36,566 --> 00:18:39,087
And the irony for us was that within a couple years,

347
00:18:39,187 --> 00:18:40,447
everything was a strategy game.

348
00:18:40,467 --> 00:18:41,888
It was a real-time strategy game.

349
00:18:41,948 --> 00:18:43,849
It was a space-based strategy game.

350
00:18:44,529 --> 00:18:46,650
So we claimed to have made the world safe

351
00:18:46,870 --> 00:18:51,192
for strategy gaming by making associations.

352
00:18:51,212 --> 00:18:53,073
We had to fight battles inside the company, too.

353
00:18:53,093 --> 00:18:54,854
I mean, the company wasn't too excited about it.

354
00:18:54,874 --> 00:18:56,754
They wanted more flight sims and things like that.

355
00:18:57,375 --> 00:18:59,236
doing a turn-based strategy game was not

356
00:19:00,136 --> 00:19:02,538
enthusiastically embraced by the management of the company.

357
00:19:03,218 --> 00:19:06,040
It was a revolutionary concept at the time.

358
00:19:06,060 --> 00:19:07,741
Until it started to sell and the critical reviews

359
00:19:07,761 --> 00:19:09,042
started coming in, then they were real happy.

360
00:19:09,062 --> 00:19:10,142
They want another one of those, please.

361
00:19:12,123 --> 00:19:12,604
Take two.

362
00:19:13,204 --> 00:19:13,664
Take two of those.

363
00:19:16,639 --> 00:19:19,121
Great leaders.

364
00:19:21,963 --> 00:19:24,185
Another thing that amazed and surprised us

365
00:19:24,325 --> 00:19:28,809
was the Gandhi phenomenon, the Gandhi meme,

366
00:19:30,010 --> 00:19:31,371
making the world safe for Gandhi.

367
00:19:33,812 --> 00:19:39,417
This is a phenomenon steeped in mystery and legend.

368
00:19:39,537 --> 00:19:42,379
But our theory is that.

369
00:19:44,193 --> 00:19:51,496
Gandhi was not really programmed to be more of a warmonger than anybody else, but it was so out of

370
00:19:51,576 --> 00:19:57,498
character for him and kind of really illustrated that the game is not about reproducing history,

371
00:19:57,598 --> 00:20:05,320
but creating your own historical story. So whenever Gandhi came up with a bad attitude,

372
00:20:05,600 --> 00:20:09,741
it was something that people really noticed and remarked upon.

373
00:20:10,482 --> 00:20:15,425
But the idea of meeting the great leaders I think kind of goes along with one of the

374
00:20:15,465 --> 00:20:17,426
fundamental things that we wanted to do with Civ.

375
00:20:18,087 --> 00:20:22,370
And Bruce and I have talked about this, that we did our research in the children's section

376
00:20:22,410 --> 00:20:27,153
of the library, that we were not trying to create a game that was about all the obscure

377
00:20:27,213 --> 00:20:30,695
historical facts that we happen to know because we read the right book.

378
00:20:31,176 --> 00:20:33,857
It was about things that everybody would be familiar with.

379
00:20:34,638 --> 00:20:39,122
And that allowed players to feel at home,

380
00:20:39,542 --> 00:20:43,325
to feel comfortable, to feel smart about the concepts

381
00:20:43,365 --> 00:20:46,007
that were in the game because they were familiar with them

382
00:20:46,047 --> 00:20:46,828
or had heard about them.

383
00:20:47,929 --> 00:20:49,750
And also they were kind of interacting

384
00:20:49,810 --> 00:20:52,432
on a peer-to-peer level with great figures like.

385
00:20:53,453 --> 00:20:56,394
Genghis Khan or Caesar or great leaders.

386
00:20:56,454 --> 00:20:59,015
So this was the role we wanted to put you in.

387
00:20:59,035 --> 00:21:02,597
This idea of building a civilization

388
00:21:02,637 --> 00:21:04,858
and being a great leader and being able to interact

389
00:21:04,898 --> 00:21:07,379
with these other leaders, I think really strengthened

390
00:21:08,439 --> 00:21:10,600
that role-playing aspect of the game.

391
00:21:10,620 --> 00:21:16,082
I was gonna say something, I can't remember what it was.

392
00:21:16,102 --> 00:21:16,462
Sorry.

393
00:21:17,468 --> 00:21:21,111
So the kind of the byline that we used,

394
00:21:21,371 --> 00:21:23,413
it's good to be king, I think that might be

395
00:21:23,433 --> 00:21:24,374
by Mel Brooks, but.

396
00:21:24,414 --> 00:21:25,956
It was interesting, because the idea was that

397
00:21:26,016 --> 00:21:27,637
I'm a god in this game, I'm a player,

398
00:21:27,657 --> 00:21:29,479
and I'm running the whole show here,

399
00:21:30,119 --> 00:21:32,021
but then you add this layer in where you put

400
00:21:32,061 --> 00:21:34,604
these leaders in, and so he gave you a dual personality,

401
00:21:34,644 --> 00:21:37,887
like I am now Stalin, or I am now Genghis Khan.

402
00:21:38,727 --> 00:21:40,889
I didn't give it that much thought,

403
00:21:40,909 --> 00:21:42,591
but you put it in there, and I think it worked.

404
00:21:44,027 --> 00:21:51,232
Yeah, I think there's always a question in a game of what do you ask the player to do and what does the computer kind of do automatically.

405
00:21:51,793 --> 00:22:02,340
And by keeping this idea in mind that you're the great leader, that really clarified a lot of the decisions in terms of what the player would do and what would kind of be done automatically.

406
00:22:02,360 --> 00:22:07,243
I also want to say, I think that we borrowed from, let's say, the children's section of the library.

407
00:22:07,724 --> 00:22:09,204
But I think there was two things about that.

408
00:22:09,384 --> 00:22:11,625
One is that they have lots of pictures in those books.

409
00:22:12,185 --> 00:22:13,286
And when you're dealing with artists,

410
00:22:13,326 --> 00:22:15,427
you need to have images that they can work with

411
00:22:15,447 --> 00:22:16,287
to make the product.

412
00:22:16,307 --> 00:22:17,448
Now you were making most of the art,

413
00:22:17,508 --> 00:22:20,809
but this is a small team a long time ago.

414
00:22:20,849 --> 00:22:22,910
And Sid did the programming, the design, and the artwork.

415
00:22:25,611 --> 00:22:27,292
So the pictures were helpful going forward

416
00:22:27,312 --> 00:22:28,632
in the years ahead when you had to come up

417
00:22:28,652 --> 00:22:29,453
with the images to tell people.

418
00:22:29,513 --> 00:22:31,293
And the other thing was that, what was the other thing?

419
00:22:32,174 --> 00:22:32,974
It's already gone again.

420
00:22:33,534 --> 00:22:35,755
Well, Bruce, I'm glad you mentioned our team

421
00:22:35,795 --> 00:22:36,176
because...

422
00:22:38,549 --> 00:22:45,051
get the small violin out. There were only about 10 of us on the team at the end and just the two

423
00:22:45,091 --> 00:22:54,593
of us, Bruce and I, worked on the project for most of the time. We had 640K in our IBM PC. We

424
00:22:54,633 --> 00:22:58,074
had 16 colors in our EGA palette that we could not change.

425
00:22:59,134 --> 00:23:02,736
And eventually we got VGA with 256 glorious colors.

426
00:23:03,716 --> 00:23:06,758
It was a very different time, obviously, technically.

427
00:23:07,358 --> 00:23:08,559
But I think what it allowed us to do

428
00:23:08,599 --> 00:23:11,180
was focus most of our energy on the game design.

429
00:23:11,580 --> 00:23:14,642
And players were willing to use their imagination

430
00:23:14,702 --> 00:23:16,082
to add a lot of the elements that we

431
00:23:16,122 --> 00:23:17,123
couldn't create at the time.

432
00:23:17,183 --> 00:23:19,364
And that actually was a pretty good trade-off, I think,

433
00:23:19,404 --> 00:23:19,684
for us.

434
00:23:21,125 --> 00:23:22,866
As we mentioned, we started the game in early 1990.

435
00:23:25,391 --> 00:23:27,333
actually stopped working on it,

436
00:23:28,013 --> 00:23:29,834
finished another game called Cover Action,

437
00:23:30,494 --> 00:23:31,795
and came back to this game,

438
00:23:32,876 --> 00:23:34,917
and eventually shipped it in late 1991.

439
00:23:35,177 --> 00:23:38,159
Probably was early 91, yeah.

440
00:23:38,339 --> 00:23:39,920
Sometime in 91 it was early, I think.

441
00:23:40,841 --> 00:23:43,803
So overall, I think we spent less than a year

442
00:23:43,823 --> 00:23:46,825
in developing the original version of the game.

443
00:23:49,758 --> 00:23:52,560
One thing about the artwork is that as the time goes by,

444
00:23:52,580 --> 00:23:54,902
I come from the school, I mean the first

445
00:23:55,623 --> 00:23:57,504
personal computer game I worked on had four colors,

446
00:23:57,584 --> 00:24:00,666
CGA graphics, and so I always came up with the school

447
00:24:00,686 --> 00:24:02,408
that the game has gotta be really interesting

448
00:24:02,428 --> 00:24:03,889
and fun to play, because you're not gonna

449
00:24:03,929 --> 00:24:05,170
wow anybody with how it looks.

450
00:24:05,790 --> 00:24:08,652
And then, you know, with the 256 colors in us,

451
00:24:08,712 --> 00:24:09,993
and we could do really interesting things,

452
00:24:10,033 --> 00:24:12,055
but I'm still pushing back about,

453
00:24:12,095 --> 00:24:13,196
let's don't put a lot of money in art,

454
00:24:13,336 --> 00:24:14,036
art's not important.

455
00:24:14,437 --> 00:24:15,838
And then, you know, I had partners by then,

456
00:24:15,858 --> 00:24:16,939
and they said, no, no, no, we're gonna make

457
00:24:16,959 --> 00:24:18,079
this incredibly beautiful.

458
00:24:18,680 --> 00:24:19,821
I said, well, okay, go ahead.

459
00:24:19,841 --> 00:24:21,562
And it made a big difference when Age of Empires

460
00:24:21,623 --> 00:24:22,944
was really, really nice looking.

461
00:24:23,484 --> 00:24:25,046
The sun was always shining, it was pretty,

462
00:24:25,066 --> 00:24:26,587
it was outdoors, it was nice.

463
00:24:26,887 --> 00:24:27,588
I think it made a difference,

464
00:24:27,628 --> 00:24:28,829
and I was not prepared for that,

465
00:24:28,849 --> 00:24:31,631
because I come from the stone ages of game design,

466
00:24:31,671 --> 00:24:32,892
when we didn't care about colors,

467
00:24:32,912 --> 00:24:33,913
there were no colors to work with.

468
00:24:35,942 --> 00:24:37,823
Speaking of the time we took to make the game, Bruce,

469
00:24:37,843 --> 00:24:39,424
I think you have a fascinating anecdote

470
00:24:39,484 --> 00:24:42,306
about the cost involved in making these games.

471
00:24:42,626 --> 00:24:45,608
Oh, well, I don't remember civilization per se,

472
00:24:45,628 --> 00:24:48,649
but I was asked to do a budget analysis for Railroad Tycoon.

473
00:24:48,669 --> 00:24:49,450
When we got done with it,

474
00:24:49,510 --> 00:24:50,830
one of the management guys asked me to do it.

475
00:24:51,251 --> 00:24:52,671
So I calculated the people who worked on it,

476
00:24:53,012 --> 00:24:55,073
what they got paid, essentially, and the time.

477
00:24:55,633 --> 00:24:57,114
And it came out that Railroad Tycoon

478
00:24:57,134 --> 00:24:58,094
had cost the company $167,000 to make.

479
00:25:00,917 --> 00:25:03,280
And this was in 1989 or 1990 or something like that.

480
00:25:03,700 --> 00:25:04,461
I was like, wow.

481
00:25:04,561 --> 00:25:07,064
I mean, we can't hire a great programmer

482
00:25:07,084 --> 00:25:08,586
for that kind of money, it seems like today.

483
00:25:08,906 --> 00:25:09,427
For one year.

484
00:25:09,447 --> 00:25:12,510
And Civ was similar, I think.

485
00:25:12,931 --> 00:25:13,071
Yeah.

486
00:25:15,234 --> 00:25:20,576
So, here's one of the great controversies of civilization.

487
00:25:20,696 --> 00:25:22,938
Perhaps one of the things we didn't do quite as well

488
00:25:22,998 --> 00:25:24,018
as we could have done.

489
00:25:24,038 --> 00:25:26,539
I don't know if you were around in the Civ I days,

