00:25:29,881 --> 00:25:31,802
or the other of this controversy.

492
00:25:33,163 --> 00:25:34,384
Just to refresh your memory,

493
00:25:35,304 --> 00:25:38,466
the question was, can a spearman defeat a battleship?

494
00:25:40,155 --> 00:25:45,117
Some people believed it could, some people believed it could not. In the game it could,

495
00:25:45,817 --> 00:25:52,080
not all the time, but the Gandhi phenomenon where something weird happens once, you assume

496
00:25:52,140 --> 00:25:59,243
it's a standard part of the game, this became one of the early controversies of the game,

497
00:25:59,263 --> 00:26:04,985
whether it was okay for a spearman to once in a while defeat a battleship.

498
00:26:07,825 --> 00:26:13,371
My claim was mathematically speaking, the spearman had a defense of two and the battleship had an

499
00:26:13,411 --> 00:26:20,497
attack of 16. So, you know, it could happen. The math could work out in that fashion. Other

500
00:26:20,517 --> 00:26:27,664
people with kind of visual, who looked at the world visually and saw a battleship and a spearman

501
00:26:27,704 --> 00:26:28,785
were not convinced.

502
00:26:30,759 --> 00:26:34,241
And interestingly enough, combat,

503
00:26:34,641 --> 00:26:36,723
if we look back at the history of Civilization

504
00:26:36,843 --> 00:26:38,664
and the various iterations of the game,

505
00:26:39,065 --> 00:26:41,626
is probably the one area that has changed the most.

506
00:26:41,687 --> 00:26:44,308
That we are, we're kind of constantly looking at

507
00:26:44,489 --> 00:26:48,151
a new way to handle combat.

508
00:26:48,251 --> 00:26:51,354
Because there's a tension between

509
00:26:52,369 --> 00:26:56,892
the view that we give you of the world as the great leader,

510
00:26:56,952 --> 00:27:00,373
that you're planning cities and you're exploring continents

511
00:27:00,834 --> 00:27:02,535
and you're deciding which wonders to build.

512
00:27:02,555 --> 00:27:04,676
And on the other hand, we're kind of getting you down

513
00:27:05,236 --> 00:27:06,977
into the nitty gritty of the combat system.

514
00:27:06,997 --> 00:27:08,878
You're moving your units, you're stacking them,

515
00:27:08,898 --> 00:27:11,839
you're deciding where to, so there's kind of a tension

516
00:27:11,879 --> 00:27:14,401
between the role that you play as the king

517
00:27:14,501 --> 00:27:17,162
over most of your civilization and your,

518
00:27:18,522 --> 00:27:21,764
your role as far as combat is concerned. So at various times

519
00:27:21,784 --> 00:27:24,645
we've actually considered going to a separate map to resolve

520
00:27:24,685 --> 00:27:28,787
combat because combat can be significant in the outcome of

521
00:27:28,807 --> 00:27:33,610
the game. We've kind of dealt with the spearman versus

522
00:27:33,650 --> 00:27:36,751
battleship controversy by adding hit points in multiple rounds of

523
00:27:36,811 --> 00:27:40,153
combat and things like that to make it somewhat less likely

524
00:27:40,613 --> 00:27:42,494
that the spearman will defeat the battleship.

525
00:27:43,735 --> 00:27:45,417
With more recent iterations of Civ,

526
00:27:45,457 --> 00:27:47,880
there's one unit per tile,

527
00:27:47,920 --> 00:27:50,603
there's different stacking rules and things like that.

528
00:27:52,185 --> 00:27:55,709
The original Civ game had a concept called zones of control

529
00:27:55,789 --> 00:27:58,612
which came from Wargaming,

530
00:27:58,693 --> 00:28:01,716
which was probably the worst idea that we put in the game.

531
00:28:02,437 --> 00:28:03,638
But it reflected...

532
00:28:04,981 --> 00:28:10,429
my vision kind of how combat was going to work in this game. I was imagining you'd create lines of

533
00:28:10,549 --> 00:28:17,099
units at your borders and you'd be trying to hold the other civs back and it would be a very kind

534
00:28:17,139 --> 00:28:21,325
of look like a World War II type of strategy game.

535
00:28:22,166 --> 00:28:24,867
That turned out to be not at all how the game was played.

536
00:28:25,147 --> 00:28:29,790
The stacks of doom was kind of the typical mechanism,

537
00:28:30,290 --> 00:28:33,051
putting together a bunch of units and moving them around.

538
00:28:33,632 --> 00:28:37,133
And the cities became really very much the focus

539
00:28:37,173 --> 00:28:39,815
of where combat took place, which actually worked well

540
00:28:39,915 --> 00:28:43,737
because it was a lot easier, smoother,

541
00:28:44,277 --> 00:28:48,339
and allowed you to focus energy on other parts of the game

542
00:28:48,379 --> 00:28:49,760
as well as just the combat.

543
00:28:50,520 --> 00:28:55,123
But something we had no, that I certainly had no idea of it,

544
00:28:55,164 --> 00:28:57,025
that when we first put things together,

545
00:28:57,725 --> 00:28:59,186
the rules that I were creating for combat

546
00:28:59,226 --> 00:29:01,768
were focused around this more kind of spread out,

547
00:29:01,928 --> 00:29:03,629
war game-y type of combat.

548
00:29:05,150 --> 00:29:08,012
But certainly with Civ 1 and then with the succeeding Civs,

549
00:29:08,052 --> 00:29:10,313
we kind of understood what was happening.

550
00:29:10,354 --> 00:29:11,694
And some of the changes that have been made

551
00:29:11,734 --> 00:29:13,696
in the more recent Civs are almost actually trying

552
00:29:13,716 --> 00:29:15,697
to get back to that more spread out combat

553
00:29:15,737 --> 00:29:18,219
and less about the stacks of doom.

554
00:29:20,899 --> 00:29:28,021
One of the other things we did with Civ was we tried to make very clear what the considerations

555
00:29:28,041 --> 00:29:29,361
were that went into combat.

556
00:29:29,401 --> 00:29:34,002
We gave each unit an attack factor, a defense factor, and a movement factor, and those were

557
00:29:34,302 --> 00:29:36,023
printed right on the unit, right in your face.

558
00:29:36,743 --> 00:29:41,545
And so that with all the systems in the game, we tried to make it very clear how they worked.

559
00:29:41,965 --> 00:29:45,509
So you weren't spending your mental energy trying to decipher the systems.

560
00:29:45,569 --> 00:29:49,974
You were spending your mental energy imagining how you would use those systems that you understood,

561
00:29:50,895 --> 00:29:55,981
how they interacted and how you would use them to accomplish your purposes in the game.

562
00:29:56,502 --> 00:29:58,965
But with combat...

563
00:29:59,565 --> 00:30:06,887
It was definitely a work in progress and I think we're still constantly adjusting how it works

564
00:30:08,567 --> 00:30:13,469
and relates to the other parts of the game because there's that tension between how important it is

565
00:30:13,549 --> 00:30:21,290
and what role you have. But I'll admit that I may have dropped the ball here as far as combat is

566
00:30:21,310 --> 00:30:21,771
concerned.

567
00:30:24,462 --> 00:30:28,966
Hey, I made peace with it. I mean, I think I probably raised the issue that I was the first guy to ever deal with it

568
00:30:29,026 --> 00:30:30,667
So I probably raised it first. I mean, how is this?

569
00:30:31,388 --> 00:30:34,410
Crummy ancient unit defeating this modern warship. It doesn't make any sense to me

570
00:30:34,430 --> 00:30:37,733
You know, this ship is on the coast and here's this guy in the land. I attack him

571
00:30:37,753 --> 00:30:40,996
I should have just blown this guy to smithereens. No. No, I lost my battleship. I don't get it

572
00:30:41,837 --> 00:30:46,501
So this is the kind of conversation we have and he'd say well, he explained it to me and I said, okay

573
00:30:47,415 --> 00:30:48,055
Okay, it's fine.

574
00:30:48,135 --> 00:30:48,995
I'll live with that.

575
00:30:49,555 --> 00:30:51,116
And I can think, I can play chess,

576
00:30:51,276 --> 00:30:54,017
and the pawn can kill the queen on the right circumstance.

577
00:30:54,517 --> 00:30:56,698
I mean, so, I mean, it's a game.

578
00:30:56,758 --> 00:30:59,699
It's not, we're not trying to model reality here.

579
00:30:59,719 --> 00:31:03,740
It's a game, and so I made that decision myself,

580
00:31:03,760 --> 00:31:05,441
and then I had to explain it to the next 50 guys

581
00:31:05,461 --> 00:31:07,141
that marched into my room complaining,

582
00:31:07,161 --> 00:31:07,862
because this is stupid.

583
00:31:07,882 --> 00:31:08,962
So it's your fault.

584
00:31:09,022 --> 00:31:10,502
You did not convince me to change.

585
00:31:10,542 --> 00:31:11,843
One of my jobs was to shield you

586
00:31:11,883 --> 00:31:12,903
from everybody else in the company

587
00:31:12,923 --> 00:31:14,044
who was upset about something.

588
00:31:14,084 --> 00:31:16,084
So they'd march down to my office and say,

589
00:31:16,104 --> 00:31:16,945
what is going on with this?

590
00:31:17,645 --> 00:31:21,112
And I'm going you know, I have to explain it again. I should have put a board on my door

591
00:31:21,152 --> 00:31:25,240
This is the problem with spearmen with the battleships. You know, don't bother me about it. This is the answer right here

592
00:31:28,526 --> 00:31:29,127
Thank You Bruce

593
00:31:30,986 --> 00:31:35,228
So another thing that we introduced with Civ 1 was the

594
00:31:35,268 --> 00:31:40,750
idea of the tech tree. And again, in hindsight, this seems

595
00:31:41,170 --> 00:31:46,573
so classic, so characteristic of the Civ game. And I wish I

596
00:31:46,613 --> 00:31:49,934
remembered the moment when we said, hey, a tech tree would be

597
00:31:49,994 --> 00:31:52,695
cool. Wouldn't that be cool? Wouldn't that be an idea that

598
00:31:52,795 --> 00:31:56,437
could last for 25 years and not only in our games but in many

599
00:31:56,497 --> 00:31:59,078
other games? I don't remember that moment.

600
00:31:59,477 --> 00:32:07,273
But I do remember having a book where kind of the timeline of history was kind of laid

601
00:32:07,413 --> 00:32:09,798
out horizontally and all these different...

602
00:32:11,290 --> 00:32:15,092
unique events were kind of pegged to their specific eras and times.

603
00:32:15,232 --> 00:32:20,155
And I'm going to guess that that was kind of the genesis of this idea,

604
00:32:20,175 --> 00:32:22,517
that one thing would lead to another.

605
00:32:22,797 --> 00:32:27,600
And it fell so wonderfully into our idea of starting very small

606
00:32:27,640 --> 00:32:32,702
and then gradually kind of unpeeling the onion

607
00:32:32,923 --> 00:32:35,244
and giving you more and more interesting things to do.

608
00:32:36,084 --> 00:32:37,885
And I think it also kind of...

609
00:32:40,068 --> 00:32:42,690
felt very Civish, this idea of,

610
00:32:44,311 --> 00:32:45,873
where on the one hand we had a war game,

611
00:32:45,893 --> 00:32:48,715
we also had a game where science was important.

612
00:32:49,235 --> 00:32:51,597
It was kind of a fairly new idea at the time,

613
00:32:51,998 --> 00:32:55,500
but really, science was gonna be an important part

614
00:32:55,520 --> 00:32:58,223
of this game, and how well you did,

615
00:32:58,243 --> 00:32:59,924
how well you managed it was gonna be significant

616
00:32:59,964 --> 00:33:01,765
in terms of your outcomes.

617
00:33:01,846 --> 00:33:06,910
So, the tech tree seemed to kind of encapsulate

618
00:33:07,050 --> 00:33:09,211
what we were trying to do with the Civ game.

619
00:33:09,572 --> 00:33:10,272
I love the tech tree.

620
00:33:10,312 --> 00:33:11,894
I was like, how do I get the railroads?

621
00:33:11,934 --> 00:33:13,475
I mean, what do I gotta do to get the railroads?

622
00:33:13,495 --> 00:33:15,156
Because the railroads, I can move my units

623
00:33:15,256 --> 00:33:16,998
all over my empire with one click.

624
00:33:17,258 --> 00:33:18,039
They can go anywhere.

625
00:33:18,059 --> 00:33:19,980
I was like, what a great thing this is.

626
00:33:20,501 --> 00:33:22,322
It was cool, it was fun to come up with the names

627
00:33:22,362 --> 00:33:24,004
for civil, it was part of our research.

628
00:33:24,724 --> 00:33:25,805
Again, maybe the children's section,

629
00:33:25,845 --> 00:33:27,386
but what were the important technologies

630
00:33:27,426 --> 00:33:28,607
in thinking about, like the stirrup?

631
00:33:28,647 --> 00:33:29,808
I remember thinking about the stirrup.

632
00:33:30,496 --> 00:33:37,017
because I'd read histories of warfare and the horsemen in battle had been like a side

633
00:33:37,057 --> 00:33:40,778
show for most of ancient times until they had a stirrup.

634
00:33:40,818 --> 00:33:44,839
And now the entire power of the horse can be pointed right at the end of your lance.

635
00:33:44,859 --> 00:33:45,739
It's catching your arm.

636
00:33:45,779 --> 00:33:49,620
Now the horse is hitting somebody, not just you with your stupid little spear.

637
00:33:49,980 --> 00:33:51,621
And it changed warfare for a couple hundred years.

638
00:33:51,641 --> 00:33:53,341
I don't think the stirrup is in our text.

639
00:33:53,441 --> 00:33:54,541
Come on, it's got to be in there.

640
00:33:55,567 --> 00:33:56,608
I don't know, it should have been.

641
00:33:56,628 --> 00:33:57,549
It's not in our game.

642
00:33:57,569 --> 00:33:58,630
I swear it's in our game.

643
00:33:59,150 --> 00:34:00,952
Maybe it was the Age of Empires then, I don't know.

644
00:34:00,972 --> 00:34:03,755
But I, it's the same line of thinking.

645
00:34:03,775 --> 00:34:05,397
It's the same thinking that here's something

646
00:34:05,437 --> 00:34:07,719
to change the world, at least temporarily.

647
00:34:09,220 --> 00:34:10,642
Let's move on, let's move on.

648
00:34:11,062 --> 00:34:11,803
Wait, I'm looking for.

649
00:34:14,238 --> 00:34:17,181
So one of the things that's fun,

650
00:34:17,321 --> 00:34:18,202
stirrup was very important.

651
00:34:18,703 --> 00:34:22,367
One of the things that's fun is to kind of look back

652
00:34:22,687 --> 00:34:26,010
and contrast how we saw things back in that time

653
00:34:26,111 --> 00:34:28,933
and how things have evolved over the course

654
00:34:28,974 --> 00:34:30,135
of many Civ games.

655
00:34:30,915 --> 00:34:34,157
And Bruce mentioned the railroads and the,

656
00:34:34,738 --> 00:34:36,919
what we certainly discovered over time

657
00:34:36,959 --> 00:34:40,701
that people would min-max and analyze the tech tree

658
00:34:41,301 --> 00:34:43,182
and have these specific technologies

659
00:34:43,202 --> 00:34:44,563
that they were targeting.

660
00:34:44,663 --> 00:34:48,345
And they would have track back seven iterations

661
00:34:48,505 --> 00:34:51,407
as to what technologies they would need to research

662
00:34:51,427 --> 00:34:53,768
to get to, gunpowder I think was often a favorite.

663
00:34:54,429 --> 00:34:59,337
and that was very contrary to how I saw the tech tree

664
00:34:59,377 --> 00:35:01,260
initially, in fact, in Civ 1,

665
00:35:03,600 --> 00:35:06,343
You might have earned the prerequisites for gunpowder,

666
00:35:06,383 --> 00:35:08,945
let's say, but there was a small chance

667
00:35:08,965 --> 00:35:12,168
that it wouldn't show up in your list of choices

668
00:35:12,288 --> 00:35:15,291
because my thinking was, well, they didn't know

669
00:35:15,371 --> 00:35:18,754
that they were gonna be able to invent gunpowder

670
00:35:18,774 --> 00:35:19,295
at this time.

671
00:35:19,795 --> 00:35:21,917
It was like they were finding their way

672
00:35:21,957 --> 00:35:26,701
through this mysterious cloud of science possibilities

673
00:35:26,902 --> 00:35:29,284
and boy, did we get some complaints about that.

674
00:35:30,865 --> 00:35:36,847
So it was what we did not anticipate was how intensely

675
00:35:36,867 --> 00:35:38,848
and how seriously and how analytically people

676
00:35:38,888 --> 00:35:40,509
would play this game.

677
00:35:41,250 --> 00:35:46,432
And that was definitely something that changed in Civ 2.

678
00:35:46,592 --> 00:35:48,633
And in some of the later Civs, it would actually say,

679
00:35:49,193 --> 00:35:51,775
if you want gunpowder, which is like eight leaves

680
00:35:51,835 --> 00:35:54,016
down the tree, you might want to go this direction.

681
00:35:54,836 --> 00:35:56,917
And I was like, oh, that's so wrong.

682
00:35:56,937 --> 00:36:00,377
So it was just like the first appearance of the optimizer

683
00:36:00,437 --> 00:36:01,158
in playing games?

684
00:36:01,238 --> 00:36:01,938
I mean, I don't know.

685
00:36:01,978 --> 00:36:03,018
The min-max player.

686
00:36:03,098 --> 00:36:05,719
One of the things that we certainly have identified

687
00:36:05,759 --> 00:36:07,479
are lots of different personality styles

688
00:36:07,779 --> 00:36:08,719
in terms of playing Civ.

689
00:36:08,779 --> 00:36:14,001
And kind of the tech tree optimizer is such a person.

690
00:36:14,161 --> 00:36:17,382
And I'm always amazed by StarCraft players

691
00:36:17,422 --> 00:36:21,943
that have, again, that same idea, the very specific actions

692
00:36:21,963 --> 00:36:23,203
that you take to play the game.

693
00:36:23,623 --> 00:36:23,703
And.

694
00:36:24,618 --> 00:36:28,262
That's one way to play, but to me, that kind of takes a lot of the fun out of it.

695
00:36:28,322 --> 00:36:35,029
So I guess I'm more drawn to games that are going to surprise me or give me a different challenge every time.

696
00:36:35,089 --> 00:36:36,610
I think that's a question of taste.

697
00:36:36,650 --> 00:36:40,534
I mean, because I like the fact that our maps are randomly generated.

698
00:36:40,554 --> 00:36:42,676
You know, the game was different every time you played.

699
00:36:43,022 --> 00:36:47,367
Now, like the StarCraft minimizer,

700
00:36:47,587 --> 00:36:48,668
he loves the map speed.

701
00:36:48,809 --> 00:36:51,552
A guy told me once, a guy at Blizzard told me once,

702
00:36:51,592 --> 00:36:52,473
he got a letter from a guy.

703
00:36:52,813 --> 00:36:55,236
He said, if you move this item one pixel to the north,

704
00:36:55,296 --> 00:36:56,838
I will never lose StarCraft again.

705
00:36:57,694 --> 00:36:59,115
That caused me so much problem.

706
00:36:59,155 --> 00:37:00,877
If you just move it one pixel, I will never lose.

707
00:37:01,237 --> 00:37:02,778
And he had to optimize the game to that extent.

708
00:37:02,838 --> 00:37:04,720
So that's a different style of play.

709
00:37:05,120 --> 00:37:07,682
People who like civilization probably were not that guy.

710
00:37:07,983 --> 00:37:09,604
That's certainly something that's been a part of Civ

711
00:37:09,624 --> 00:37:11,666
all the way through, is the idea of random maps,

712
00:37:12,106 --> 00:37:14,628
scenarios, difficulty levels, many different ways

713
00:37:14,688 --> 00:37:16,009
of allowing you to replay the game

714
00:37:16,049 --> 00:37:18,972
and have a different experience, or a new experience,

715
00:37:19,272 --> 00:37:20,833
or a fresh experience.

716
00:37:21,033 --> 00:37:24,116
Yeah, I mean, going forward, I definitely wanted random maps

717
00:37:24,216 --> 00:37:27,078
in the games that we made going forward.

718
00:37:29,947 --> 00:37:39,961
The wonders of the world. History is so rich in stuff for us to steal. This was just cool,

719
00:37:40,161 --> 00:37:44,167
low-hanging fruit that wouldn't it be cool to build these awesome wonders?

720
00:37:46,367 --> 00:37:48,428
in the successive iterations of Civ,

721
00:37:48,468 --> 00:37:50,630
we were able to actually give you wonder movies

722
00:37:50,650 --> 00:37:54,872
and kind of give you some pretty dramatic payoffs

723
00:37:54,892 --> 00:37:55,652
for doing these things.

724
00:37:55,753 --> 00:38:00,515
But the idea of something that only one Civ

725
00:38:00,555 --> 00:38:01,536
in the world could build,

726
00:38:01,616 --> 00:38:03,557
and you wanted to race to be the first to do that,

727
00:38:04,497 --> 00:38:07,139
gave you another way of being aware of the other Civs

728
00:38:07,419 --> 00:38:10,321
that were in the world and what else was going on there.

729
00:38:11,001 --> 00:38:14,282
And I think it also gave you this connection

730
00:38:14,322 --> 00:38:15,362
to things that you'd heard about,

731
00:38:15,382 --> 00:38:17,763
whether it was Stonehenge or the pyramids.

732
00:38:17,823 --> 00:38:18,763
I think it was aspirational.

733
00:38:18,783 --> 00:38:20,623
I mean, I'm gonna build a great wall,

734
00:38:20,643 --> 00:38:22,144
a great pyramid of Giza.

735
00:38:22,244 --> 00:38:23,504
That's pretty cool, I get to do that.

736
00:38:23,944 --> 00:38:24,604
I wanna do that.

737
00:38:24,664 --> 00:38:27,005
I thought that was interesting, the way we did that,

738
00:38:27,105 --> 00:38:28,185
the way you did that, let's say.

739
00:38:29,645 --> 00:38:31,046
I think the wonders are very popular.

